    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-05-14T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-05-14T12:00:00-05:00" n="476"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d476">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">765.84/311: Telegram (part air)</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Geneva</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gilbert</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-05-14T18:00:00+01:00"
                            >May 14, 1935—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received May 16—8:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>174. Consulate’s 138, April 15, 7 p.m.<note n="11" xml:id="d476fn11">Not
                        printed.</note> Abyssinian Minister to France<note n="13" xml:id="d476fn13"
                        >Teclé Hawariate.</note> has addressed a note to the Secretary General dated
                    May 11 in which he requests him to advise the Council of the serious situation
                    being created by mobilization in Italy and by the despatch of more troops to
                    Eritrea and Somaliland. Recalling the conciliatory views expressed by both
                    powers before the Council in January and April of this year he states that Italy
                    has not taken the “smallest step” in the direction of arbitration. He accuses
                    Italy of approaching certain foreign governments some of whose nationals were
                    likely to be selected as arbitrators by the Ethiopian Government and of
                    requesting them to deter their nationals from accepting such appointments.
                    Reference is likewise made to a communication from the Italian Minister at Addis
                    Ababa inviting the Ethiopian Government to choose arbitrators of Ethiopian
                    nationality. He urges the Council to endeavor in accordance with article 15 of
                    the Covenant to bring about a settlement of the dispute.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gilbert</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
